The paper also discusses probabilistic programming, which is a programming paradigm that aims to ease the specification of structured probability distributions. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. 

The paper's focus on probabilistic planning through the lens of probabilistic programming suggests that it is also likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, as probabilistic programming is often used in machine learning applications. 

The paper's discussion of planning problems with growing and shrinking state spaces suggests that it is also likely to belong to the cs.RO (Robotics) sub-category, as robotics often involves planning in dynamic environments. 

Finally, the paper's discussion of non-unique prior distributions in a first-order setting suggests that it is also likely to belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category, as systems and control often involve dealing with uncertainty and probabilistic models.
